OOPS! Studio! 2023-12-14 3:31 AM
CPUs (and all components of a computer, really, but especially CPUs) produce heat when uses. The older the CPU, the higher the ratio of heat to processing power is. Modern CPU architecture is 100% about heat management. The less heat a CPU produces, the faster and more power-efficient it will be. So older CPUs = more heat. More heat means the fans need to be on more often and need to run at higher speeds to create enough air flow to carry the heat away. The fans make noise, so more fans = more noise. So older PC = more heat = more fans = more noise. Then for HDD vs SSD, HDD is "hard disk drive" and SSD is "solid-state drive" HDDs read and write data by spinning a disk under a magnetic arm. This means of storing data is cheap and old, so it was widely used in old PCs. Most newer (and high-end) PCs are now built with SSDs instead because they're way faster, more reliable, and quieter. They're quieter because they have no moving parts, where an HDD has a disk that has to be spinning the entire time data is being read or written, which makes noise. So between those two - newer PCs tend to be much quieter than old ones.
